{{Infobox Book <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = American Visions: The Epic History of Art in America | image = | caption = | author = [[Robert Hughes (critic)|Robert Hughes]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = England | language = English | subject = Non-fiction, American Art History | published = 1997 ([[Random House|The Harvill Press]]) | media_type = Print ([[Hardback]]) | pages = 635 | isbn = 978-0676527841 | oclc = 901568324 }}
'''''American Visions: The Epic History of Art in America''''' is a 1997 book by [[art critic]] [[Robert Hughes (critic)|Robert Hughes]].
==Reception== ''[[BookList]]'' called ''American Visions'' a "sensational history of American art." and wrote "The contrast between the influence of nature and of the city on American art is the fulcrum of Hughes' entire narrative ..."<ref name=buffalo/> and ''[[Choice: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries|Choice Reviews]]'' stated "The book bears the stamp of the author's aesthetic sensibilities (which value works of art for their technical competence as well as visual and intellectual qualities), his critical acuity, and his accomplished writing."<ref name=buffalo>{{cite web |url=https://www.buffalolib.org/vufind/Record/900642/Reviews |title=American visions : the epic history of art in America |website=www.buffalolib.org |publisher=Buffalo and Erie County Public Library |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>
''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' gave a starred review and described it as an "eminently readable handbook on American art.", writing "His readings of three centuries of both art works and trends are lively, detailed, and persuasive (though perhaps a bit too harsh regarding recent art), and his ultimately pessimistic take is expressed with great clarity. A meaty and illuminating excavation, full of vigor and punch..."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/robert-hughes-6/american-visions-the-epic-history-of-an-in-amer/ |title=AMERICAN VISIONS: The Epic History of An in America |date=1 March 1997 |website=www.kirkusreviews.com |publisher=Kirkus Media LLC |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> [[Publishers Weekly]] noted "this is no bland, dumbed-down survey intended to flatter its subject or its audience. Hughes writes with an aesthete's disdain for political posturing, a traditionalist's belief in the importance of technical skills (painters are frequently taken to task for their shoddy draftsmanship) and a pragmatist's contempt for mystagogical bunk.", found "his account of the contemporary scene is disappointingly brief." and concluded "This slashingly witty, briskly paced, ferociously opinionated tour of the American visual landscape is a book that even the most un-likeminded readers will love to hate."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-679-42627-1 |title=American Visions: The Epic History of Art in America |date=31 March 1997 |website=www.publishersweekly.com |publisher=PWxyz LLC|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>
A ''[[New York Times]]'' review calls it a "witty and impassioned history of American art from its beginnings to the present day", "beautiful and essential", notes that "Mr. Hughes fortunately remains the critic throughout his historical canvassing, making distinctions and judgments without taking sides." and concludes "With it, Mr. Hughes has made American art safe for the receptive alien deep inside us all."<ref>{{cite news |author=Lee Siegel |date=27 April 1997 |title=A critic interprets American art as a perpetual beginning |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/reviews/970427.27siegelt.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> ''American Visions'' has also been reviewed by the ''[[London Review of Books]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |date=30 October 1997 |title=Big Daddy |url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v19/n21/linda-nochlin/big-daddy |journal=London Review of Books |publisher=LRB Limited |volume=19 |number=21 |pages=10,11 |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Journal of American History]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |date=1998 |title=American Visions: The Epic History of Art in America. By Robert Hughes. |url=http://jah.oxfordjournals.org/content/85/1/200.2.extract |journal=The Journal of American History |publisher= |volume=85 |issue=1 |pages=200, 201 |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> and ''[[The New York Review of Books]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |date=26 June 1997 |title=Made in the USA|author=Louis Menand |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/1997/06/26/made-in-the-usa/ |journal=The New York Review of Books |publisher=NYREV, Inc. |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>
